<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">2 Samuel 3:1-39</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="24">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="39">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">And the war between the house of Saul and the house of David came to be long drawn out; and David kept getting stronger, and the house of Saul kept declining more and more.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">Meantime, sons were born to David in He&acute;bron, and his firstborn came to be Am&acute;non by A&middot;hin&acute;o&middot;am the Jez&acute;re&middot;el&middot;i&middot;tess.</span> <a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">And his second was Chil&acute;e&middot;ab by Ab&acute;i&middot;gail the wife of Na&acute;bal the Car&acute;mel&middot;ite, and the third was Ab&acute;sa&middot;lom the son of Ma&acute;a&middot;cah the daughter of Tal&acute;mai the king of Gesh&acute;ur.</span> <a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">And the fourth was Ad&middot;o&middot;ni&acute;jah the son of Hag&acute;gith, and the fifth was Sheph&middot;a&middot;ti&acute;ah the son of A&middot;bi&acute;tal.</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">And the sixth was Ith&acute;re&middot;am by Eg&acute;lah, David’s wife. These were the ones born to David in He&acute;bron.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">And it came about that while the war between the house of Saul and the house of David kept up, Ab&acute;ner himself was continually strengthening his position in the house of Saul.</span> <a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">Now Saul had had a concubine whose name was Riz&acute;pah, the daughter of A&acute;iah. Later Ish-bo&acute;sheth said to Ab&acute;ner: “Why was it that you had relations with the concubine of my father?”</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">And Ab&acute;ner got very angry at the words of Ish-bo&acute;sheth and went on to say: “Am I a dog’s head that belongs to Judah? Today I keep exercising loving-kindness toward the house of Saul your father, to his brothers and his personal friends, and I have not let you find yourself in the hand of David; and yet you call me to account for an error concerning a woman today.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">So may God do to Ab&acute;ner and so may he add to it, if, just as Jehovah swore to David, that is not the way that I shall do to him,</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">so as to transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul and to establish the throne of David over Israel and over Judah from Dan to Be&acute;er-she&acute;ba.”</span> <a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">And he was not able to say one word more in reply to Ab&acute;ner because of being afraid of him.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">Accordingly Ab&acute;ner sent messengers to David on the spot, saying: “To whom does the land belong?” adding: “Do conclude your covenant with me, and, look! my hand will be with you to turn to your side the whole of Israel.”</span> <a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">To this he said: “Good! I myself shall conclude a covenant with you. Only one thing there is that I am asking of you, saying, ‘You may not see my face except first you bring Mi&acute;chal, Saul’s daughter, when you come to see my face.’”</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">Further, David sent messengers to Ish-bo&acute;sheth, Saul’s son, saying: “Do give over my wife Mi&acute;chal, whom I engaged to myself for a hundred foreskins of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines.”</span> <a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">So Ish-bo&acute;sheth sent and took her from her husband, Pal&acute;ti&middot;el the son of La&acute;ish.</span> <a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">But her husband kept walking with her, weeping as he walked after her as far as Ba&middot;hu&acute;rim. Then Ab&acute;ner said to him: “Go, return!” At that he returned.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">Meanwhile there had come to be communication by Ab&acute;ner with the older men of Israel, saying: “Both yesterday and previously <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> proved yourselves seeking David as king over <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>.</span> <a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">And now act, for Jehovah himself said to David, ‘By the hand of David my servant I shall save my people Israel from the hand of the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines and from the hand of all their enemies.’”</span> <a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">Then Ab&acute;ner also spoke in the ears of Benjamin, after which Ab&acute;ner also went to speak in the ears of David at He&acute;bron all that was good in the eyes of Israel and in the eyes of the whole house of Benjamin.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">When Ab&acute;ner came to David at He&acute;bron, and with him twenty men, David proceeded to make a feast for Ab&acute;ner and for the men that were with him.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">Then Ab&acute;ner said to David: “Let me rise up and go and collect all Israel together to my lord the king, that they may conclude a covenant with you, and you will certainly become king over all that your soul craves.” So David sent Ab&acute;ner off, and he got on his way in peace.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">And here David’s servants and Jo&acute;ab were coming from a raid, and the spoil that they brought with them was abundant. As for Ab&acute;ner, he was not with David in He&acute;bron, for he had sent him off, and he was on his way in peace.</span> <a name="bk23" class="vsAnchor">23</a>
       <span id="vs23">And Jo&acute;ab and all the army that was with him came in, and they now reported to Jo&acute;ab, saying: “Ab&acute;ner the son of Ner came to the king, and he proceeded to send him off, and he is on his way in peace.”</span> <a name="bk24" class="vsAnchor">24</a>
       <span id="vs24">So Jo&acute;ab went in to the king and said: “What have you done? Look! Ab&acute;ner has come to you. Why was it that you sent him off so that he successfully went away?</span> <a name="bk25" class="vsAnchor">25</a>
       <span id="vs25">You well know Ab&acute;ner the son of Ner, that it was to fool you that he came and to get to know your going out and your coming in and to get to know everything that you are doing.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk26" class="vsAnchor">26</a>
       <span id="vs26">With that Jo&acute;ab went out from David and sent messengers after Ab&acute;ner, and they then had him return from the cistern of Si&acute;rah; and David himself did not know of it.</span> <a name="bk27" class="vsAnchor">27</a>
       <span id="vs27">When Ab&acute;ner returned to He&acute;bron, Jo&acute;ab now led him aside inside the gate to speak with him quietly. However, there he struck him in the abdomen, so that he died because of the blood of As&acute;a&middot;hel his brother.</span> <a name="bk28" class="vsAnchor">28</a>
       <span id="vs28">When David heard of it afterward, he at once said: “I and my kingdom, from the standpoint of Jehovah, are innocent for time indefinite of bloodguilt for Ab&acute;ner the son of Ner.</span> <a name="bk29" class="vsAnchor">29</a>
       <span id="vs29">May it whirl back upon the head of Jo&acute;ab and upon the entire house of his father, and let there not be cut off from Jo&acute;ab’s house a man with a running discharge or a leper or a man taking hold of the twirling spindle or one falling by the sword or one in need of bread!”</span> <a name="bk30" class="vsAnchor">30</a>
       <span id="vs30">As for Jo&acute;ab and A&middot;bish&acute;ai his brother, they killed Ab&acute;ner over the fact that he had put As&acute;a&middot;hel their brother to death at Gib&acute;e&middot;on in the battle.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk31" class="vsAnchor">31</a>
       <span id="vs31">Then David said to Jo&acute;ab and all the people that were with him: “Rip <span class="smallcaps">YOUR</span> garments apart and tie on sackcloth and wail before Ab&acute;ner.” Even King David was walking behind the couch.</span> <a name="bk32" class="vsAnchor">32</a>
       <span id="vs32">And they had the burial of Ab&acute;ner in He&acute;bron; and the king began to raise his voice and weep at Ab&acute;ner’s burial place, and all the people gave way to weeping.</span> <a name="bk33" class="vsAnchor">33</a>
       <span id="vs33">And the king went on to chant over Ab&acute;ner and say:</span>
</p>

<p class="p"> 
       <span id="vs33-2">“As with the death of a senseless person should Ab&acute;ner die?</span>
</p>

<p class="l"><a name="bk34" class="vsAnchor">34</a>
       <span id="vs34">Your hands had not been bound ones,<br><span class="z">And your feet had not been put into fetters of copper.</span><br><span class="z">As one falling before the sons of unrighteousness you have fallen.”</span></span>
</p>

<p> 
       <span id="vs34-4">At that all the people wept over him again.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk35" class="vsAnchor">35</a>
       <span id="vs35">Later all the people came to give David bread for consolation while it was yet that day, but David swore, saying: “So may God do to me and so may he add to it, if before the sun sets I shall taste bread or anything at all!”</span> <a name="bk36" class="vsAnchor">36</a>
       <span id="vs36">And all the people themselves took notice, and it was good in their eyes. Like everything that the king did, it was in the eyes of all the people good.</span> <a name="bk37" class="vsAnchor">37</a>
       <span id="vs37">And all the people and all Israel got to know on that day that it had not originated with the king to have Ab&acute;ner the son of Ner put to death.</span> <a name="bk38" class="vsAnchor">38</a>
       <span id="vs38">And the king went on to say to his servants: “Do <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> not know that it is a prince and a great man that has fallen this day in Israel?</span> <a name="bk39" class="vsAnchor">39</a>
       <span id="vs39">And I today am weak although anointed as king, and these men, the sons of Ze&middot;ru&acute;iah, are too severe for me. May Jehovah repay the doer of what is bad according to his own badness.”</span>
</p>
</form>

