<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">2 Samuel 21:1-22</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="24">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="22">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">Now there came to be a famine in the days of David for three years, year after year; and David proceeded to consult the face of Jehovah. Then Jehovah said: “Upon Saul and upon his house there is bloodguilt, because he put the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites to death.”</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">So the king called the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites and talked to them. (Incidentally, the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites were not of the sons of Israel, but of the remainder of the Am&acute;or&middot;ites; and the sons of Israel themselves had sworn to them, but Saul sought to strike them down in his feeling jealous for the sons of Israel and Judah.)</span> <a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">And David went on to say to the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites: “What shall I do to <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, and with what shall I make atonement, that <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> may certainly bless the inheritance of Jehovah?”</span> <a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">So the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites said to him: “It is not a matter of silver or gold for us in connection with Saul and his household, neither is it ours to put a man to death in Israel.” At that he said: “Whatever <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> are saying I shall do for <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>.”</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">At this they said to the king: “The man that exterminated us and that schemed to annihilate us from subsisting in any of the territory of Israel,</span> <a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">let there be given to us seven men of his sons; and we must expose them to Jehovah in Gib&acute;e&middot;ah of Saul, the chosen one of Jehovah.” Accordingly the king said: “I myself shall give them.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">However, the king felt compassion upon Me&middot;phib&acute;o&middot;sheth the son of Jon&acute;a&middot;than the son of Saul on account of the oath of Jehovah that was between them, between David and Jon&acute;a&middot;than the son of Saul.</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">Consequently the king took the two sons of Riz&acute;pah the daughter of A&acute;iah whom she bore to Saul, Ar&middot;mo&acute;ni and Me&middot;phib&acute;o&middot;sheth, and the five sons of Mi&acute;chal the daughter of Saul whom she bore to A&acute;dri&middot;el the son of Bar&middot;zil&acute;lai the Me&middot;hol&acute;ath&middot;ite.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">Then he gave them into the hand of the Gib&acute;e&middot;on&middot;ites and they proceeded to expose them on the mountain before Jehovah, so that the seven of them fell together; and they themselves were put to death in the first days of harvest, at the start of the barley harvest.</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">However, Riz&acute;pah the daughter of A&acute;iah took sackcloth and spread it for herself upon the rock from the start of harvest until water poured down upon them from the heavens; and she did not allow the fowls of the heavens to rest upon them by day nor the wild beasts of the field by night.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">At length it was reported to David what Riz&acute;pah the daughter of A&acute;iah, Saul’s concubine, had done.</span> <a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">So David went and took the bones of Saul and the bones of Jon&acute;a&middot;than his son from the landowners of Ja&acute;besh-gil&acute;e&middot;ad, who had stolen them from the public square of Beth-shan, where the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines had hanged them on the day that the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines struck down Saul on Gil&middot;bo&acute;a.</span> <a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">And he proceeded to bring up from there the bones of Saul and the bones of Jon&acute;a&middot;than his son; furthermore, they gathered the bones of the men being exposed.</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">Then they buried the bones of Saul and of Jon&acute;a&middot;than his son in the land of Benjamin in Ze&acute;la in the burial place of Kish his father, that they might do everything that the king had commanded. So God let himself be entreated for the land after this.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">And the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines came to have war again with Israel. Accordingly David and his servants with him went down and fought the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines; and David grew tired.</span> <a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">And Ish&acute;bi-be&acute;nob, who was among those born of the Reph&acute;a&middot;im, the weight of whose spear was three hundred shekels of copper and who was girded with a new sword, got to think of striking David down.</span> <a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">At once A&middot;bish&acute;ai the son of Ze&middot;ru&acute;iah came to his help and struck the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tine down and put him to death. At that time the men of David swore to him, saying: “You must not go out with us to the battle anymore, that you may not extinguish the lamp of Israel!”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">And it came about after this that war arose once more with the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines at Gob. Then it was that Sib&acute;be&middot;cai the Hu&acute;shath&middot;ite struck down Saph, who was among those born of the Reph&acute;a&middot;im.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">And war arose once again with the Phi&middot;lis&acute;tines at Gob, and El&middot;ha&acute;nan the son of Ja&acute;a&middot;re-or&acute;e&middot;gim the Beth&acute;le&middot;hem&middot;ite got to strike down Go&middot;li&acute;ath the Git&acute;tite, the shaft of whose spear was like the beam of loom workers.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">And war arose yet again at Gath, when there happened to be a man of extraordinary size, with six fingers on each of his hands and six toes on each of his feet, twenty-four in number; and he too had been born to the Reph&acute;a&middot;im.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">And he kept taunting Israel. Finally Jon&acute;a&middot;than the son of Shim&acute;e&middot;i, David’s brother, struck him down.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">These four had been born to the Reph&acute;a&middot;im in Gath; and they came to fall by the hand of David and by the hand of his servants.</span>
</p>
</form>

